servings: 2
author: HelloFresh
---

Trim and halve the @green beans{75%g}.

Trim the @carrot{1} and halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into roughly 1cm
wide, 5cm long batons.

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Zest then quarter the @lime{1}. Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(stalks and all).

Halve the @chilli{1} lengthways then discard the core and seeds. Finely chop.

Pour @water{300%ml}(cold, salted) into a medium #pot{} with a tight-fitting lid.

Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pot from the heat.

Keep covered for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will
continue to cook in its own steam).

Place a large #pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the pan is very hot, sear the @Irish beef strips{250%g} until cooked
through, shifting as they colour, ~{2-3%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and
equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging. Meat is safe to eat when
the outside is browned.

Once cooked, remove from the pan and set aside.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with another drizzle of @oil{to taste}, if
necessary.

Once hot, fry the carrots and green beans for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Next add the onion, chilli and @garlic, ginger & lemongrass paste{1%sachet}.

Cook until the veg is tender, stirring often, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in lime zest, @soy sauce{2%sachets}, @red Thai style paste{1%sachet}, and
@water{50%ml}.

Cook until sauce has reduced slightly, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the beef and cook until warmed through, ~{1%minute}.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water to loosen the sauce if necessary!

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between plates.

Top with the spicy beef.

Finish with a squeeze of lime juice and a sprinkling of coriander.